------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
üìò WEEK 2 ‚Äì DAY 7 JavaScript | Variables, Data Types & Operators (Deep Dive)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üéØ Goal of Day 7

‚úî Understand **variables deeply**
‚úî Learn **all JavaScript data types**
‚úî Master **operators** used in real projects

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üßæ JavaScript Variables (Deep Dive)

Variables are used to **store data**.

```js
let name = "Saakshi";
const age = 21;
```
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üîë Variable Keywords

`let`

* Block scoped
* Value can change

```js
let score = 10;
score = 20;
```

---

`const` (Recommended)

* Block scoped
* Value **cannot** be reassigned

```js
const PI = 3.14;
```

üìå Use `const` by default

---

`var` (Avoid)

* Function scoped
* Can cause bugs

```js
var city = "Delhi";
```

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üÜö let vs const vs var

| Feature     | let          | const        | var      |
| ----------- | ------------ | ------------ | -------- |
| Scope       | Block        | Block        | Function |
| Reassign    | ‚úÖ           | ‚ùå          | ‚úÖ       |
| Hoisting    | Yes (unsafe) | Yes (unsafe) | Yes      |
| Recommended | ‚úÖ           | ‚≠ê         | ‚ùå      |

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üì¶ JavaScript Data Types

JavaScript has **two categories**:

1. **Primitive**
2. **Non-Primitive (Reference)**

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üîπ Primitive Data Types

1Ô∏è‚É£ Number

```js
let num = 10;
let price = 99.99;
```

---

2Ô∏è‚É£ String

```js
let msg = "Hello";
let name = 'JS';
```

---

3Ô∏è‚É£ Boolean

```js
let isLoggedIn = true;
```

---

4Ô∏è‚É£ Undefined

```js
let x;
```

üìå Declared but no value

---

5Ô∏è‚É£ Null

```js
let data = null;
```

üìå Intentionally empty

---

6Ô∏è‚É£ BigInt

```js
let big = 12345678901234567890n;
```

üìå Used for very large numbers

---

7Ô∏è‚É£ Symbol

```js
let id = Symbol("id");
```

üìå Used for unique identifiers

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üîπ Non-Primitive Data Types

1Ô∏è‚É£ Object

```js
let user = {
  name: "Saakshi",
  age: 21
};
```

---

2Ô∏è‚É£ Array

```js
let skills = ["HTML", "CSS", "JS"];
```

---

3Ô∏è‚É£ Function

```js
function greet() {
  console.log("Hello");
}
```

---

üß™ `typeof` Operator

Used to check data type.

```js
typeof "Hello";   // string
typeof 10;        // number
typeof true;      // boolean
```

---

‚ûï JavaScript Operators

Operators are used to **perform operations** on values.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üî¢ Arithmetic Operators

| Operator | Meaning     |
| -------- | ----------- |
| `+`      | Addition    |
| `-`      | Subtraction |
| `*`      | Multiply    |
| `/`      | Divide      |
| `%`      | Modulus     |

```js
let sum = 10 + 5;
```

---

üßÆ Assignment Operators

```js
let x = 10;
x += 5;   // x = 15
```

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üîç Comparison Operators

| Operator | Use            |
| -------- | -------------- |
| `==`     | Value only     |
| `===`    | Value + Type ‚≠ê |
| `!=`     | Not equal      |
| `>` `<`  | Comparison     |

```js
10 === "10"; // false
```

üìå Always prefer `===`

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üîó Logical Operators

| Operator | Meaning |   |    |
| -------- | ------- | - | -- |
| `&&`     | AND     |   |    |
| `        |         | ` | OR |
| `!`      | NOT     |   |    |

```js
age > 18 && isLoggedIn;
```

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üîÅ Unary Operators

```js
let x = 5;
x++;   // increment
x--;   // decrement
```

---

‚ùì Ternary Operator

Short form of if-else.

```js
let result = age >= 18 ? "Adult" : "Minor";
```

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üîÑ Type Conversion

Implicit Conversion

```js
"5" + 2;   // "52"
```

---

Explicit Conversion

```js
Number("10");   // 10
String(100);    // "100"
Boolean(1);     // true
```

---

‚ö†Ô∏è Truthy & Falsy Values

Falsy Values

```js
false, 0, "", null, undefined, NaN
```

Truthy Values

```js
"hello", 1, [], {}
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

‚ùå Common Beginner Mistakes

* Using `==` instead of `===`
* Overusing `var`
* Confusing `null` & `undefined`
* Ignoring type conversion

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

üí° Best Practices

* Use `const` & `let`
* Always use `===`
* Check data types using `typeof`
* Write clean & readable code

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

‚úÖ DAY-7 Summary (Week-2)

* Variables deep understanding
* Primitive & non-primitive types
* Operators (all types)
* Type conversion
* Best practices
